http://schema.org/description.@value: Demo of the Markdown Message widget

http://schema.org/question.@value:
## Markdown Message

The Markdown Message widget allows you to write an instruction page using the popular [Markdown](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markdown) language.

This allows you to display formatted text, hyperlinks, and even images!

![sparkle emoji](https://emojipedia-us.s3.dualstack.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/thumbs/160/apple/198/sparkles_2728.png =64x64)

Note that unlike other widgets, the user can always go to the "Next" screen after a Markdown Message screen.

http://schema.org/description.@value: Demo of the Table Counter widget

http://schema.org/question.@value:
## Table Counter

The editor defines the number of rows and columns and the labels. Each table cell is a counter that the user can increment by pressing on it. The user can decrement the counter by doing a long press.

In this example, a list of names appears along the x-axis together with some behaviors along the y-axis.

http://schema.org/description.@value: Instructions for the Visual Stimulus Response widget

http://schema.org/question.@value:
## Visual Stimulus Response

The following page is an example of the Visual Stimulus Response widget. This complex widget shows the user a certain number of trials. In each trial the user is presented with a visual stimulus in the center of the screen. The user must respond to the stimuli by pressing a button at the bottom of the screen.

This widget is highly configurable. You can configure the sampling method and sampling size, whether to show the user feedback, and much more.

The following page contains a little Jeopardy! quiz.
